const QUESTIONS = {
  'Frontend Developer': {
    technical: [
      { question: 'What is the difference between var, let, and const in JavaScript?', answer: 'var is function-scoped and hoisted, which can cause unexpected behavior. let is block-scoped and can be reassigned but not re-declared. const is block-scoped and cannot be reassigned after declaration. In modern JavaScript I always prefer const by default and use let only when reassignment is needed.' },
      { question: 'How does the React Virtual DOM work?', answer: 'React maintains a lightweight in-memory representation of the real DOM. When state or props change, React creates a new Virtual DOM tree and diffs it against the previous one using reconciliation. Only changed nodes get updated in the actual DOM, making updates efficient and fast.' },
      { question: 'What is CSS specificity and how is it calculated?', answer: 'Specificity determines which CSS rule wins when multiple rules target the same element. It is calculated as: inline styles (1,0,0,0), IDs (0,1,0,0), classes/attributes (0,0,1,0), and elements (0,0,0,1). The rule with the highest specificity wins. !important overrides all specificity.' },
      { question: 'Explain the CSS Box Model.', answer: 'Every HTML element is a rectangular box with four layers: content, padding, border, and margin. By default, width and height apply only to the content. With box-sizing: border-box, width includes padding and border, making layouts more predictable. I always set box-sizing: border-box globally.' },
      { question: 'What are React Hooks? Name five important ones.', answer: 'Hooks let functional components use React features. Key ones: useState for local state, useEffect for side effects like API calls, useContext for consuming context, useRef for DOM access without re-renders, and useMemo/useCallback for performance optimisation by memoizing values and functions.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between controlled and uncontrolled components?', answer: 'A controlled component has its form data managed by React state, with value driven by state and onChange handlers. An uncontrolled component manages its own state via the DOM, accessed through refs. Controlled components are preferred for validation and keeping UI in sync with state.' },
      { question: 'How does event delegation work in JavaScript?', answer: 'Event delegation relies on event bubbling. Instead of attaching listeners to every child element, you attach a single listener to a parent and check event.target. This is more memory-efficient and automatically handles dynamically added elements.' },
      { question: 'What is the purpose of useEffect and what are its dependencies?', answer: 'useEffect runs side effects after render. An empty array means it runs once on mount, no array means every render, and specific values mean it runs when those change. The cleanup function runs before the next effect and on unmount, useful for clearing timers or subscriptions.' },
      { question: 'What is lazy loading and how do you implement it in React?', answer: 'Lazy loading defers loading components until needed, reducing initial bundle size. In React I use React.lazy() with dynamic import() and wrap components in Suspense with a fallback. For routes, I apply this to page-level components so each route loads only when navigated to.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between SSR and CSR?', answer: 'CSR sends a minimal HTML shell and renders in the browser — great for interactive apps but slower initial load and SEO challenges. SSR generates full HTML on the server per request — better for SEO and initial performance but increases server load. Next.js supports both plus Static Site Generation.' },
    ],
    conceptual: [
      { question: 'What is accessibility and why does it matter?', answer: 'Accessibility means building applications everyone can use, including people with disabilities. It matters ethically, legally, and commercially. I implement it through semantic HTML, ARIA attributes, sufficient colour contrast, keyboard navigation, and screen reader testing.' },
      { question: 'Explain the concept of responsive design.', answer: 'Responsive design creates UIs that adapt to different screen sizes. I use CSS Flexbox and Grid, relative units, media queries, and a mobile-first approach — designing the smallest screen first and progressively enhancing for larger ones. Tailwind CSS makes this efficient with responsive prefixes.' },
      { question: 'What is code splitting and why is it important?', answer: 'Code splitting divides a JavaScript bundle into smaller chunks loaded on demand, reducing initial load time. Users only download code for features they are using. React supports this via dynamic import() and React.lazy(). Vite and webpack handle chunking automatically.' },
      { question: 'What is the purpose of a CSS preprocessor like SASS?', answer: 'SASS extends CSS with variables, nesting, mixins, and partials making stylesheets more maintainable. It compiles to standard CSS. While Tailwind has reduced the need for SASS in many projects, SASS remains valuable for complex design systems and theming.' },
      { question: 'What is a PWA?', answer: 'A Progressive Web App uses modern web APIs for app-like experiences. Requirements include a web manifest for installability, a service worker for offline support, HTTPS, and responsive design. PWAs can be installed, work offline, send push notifications, and load fast.' },
      { question: 'How do you optimise the performance of a React application?', answer: 'At component level: React.memo, useMemo, useCallback to prevent unnecessary re-renders. At bundle level: code splitting and tree shaking. At asset level: image compression and lazy loading. At network level: caching strategies. I always profile with React DevTools before optimising.' },
      { question: 'What is the purpose of a design system?', answer: 'A design system is a collection of reusable components and style guidelines ensuring visual consistency. It speeds development, reduces inconsistencies, and makes the codebase more maintainable. Storybook helps document and test components in isolation.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between debouncing and throttling?', answer: 'Debouncing delays execution until a specified time after the last call — ideal for search inputs. Throttling limits execution to once per interval — ideal for scroll or resize events. Both prevent performance issues from too-frequent function calls.' },
      { question: 'What are Web Vitals?', answer: 'Web Vitals are Google metrics for real-world UX: LCP (Largest Contentful Paint) measures loading, FID (First Input Delay) measures interactivity, CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift) measures visual stability. They directly impact SEO rankings. I monitor them using Lighthouse and PageSpeed Insights.' },
      { question: 'What is micro-frontend architecture?', answer: 'Micro-frontends apply microservice principles to the UI — different teams own and independently deploy separate sections of a large application. Each section can use its own framework. They are composed using iframes, Web Components, or module federation. They solve large-team scaling problems but add integration complexity.' },
    ],
    hr: [
      { question: 'Tell me about yourself.', answer: 'I am a frontend developer with strong React, JavaScript, and CSS skills. I completed my B.Tech in Computer Science and have built projects including a full-stack e-commerce application and a real-time dashboard. I am passionate about creating intuitive UIs and turning complex requirements into clean, accessible web experiences.' },
      { question: 'What is your greatest strength?', answer: 'My greatest strength is breaking complex UI problems into manageable components systematically. I pay close attention to detail in both code quality and visual output. I also pick up new tools quickly — I self-taught Tailwind CSS and Framer Motion in two weeks, which significantly improved my project quality.' },
      { question: 'Describe a challenging project and how you handled it.', answer: 'During my final year project I built a real-time collaborative dashboard using Socket.io for the first time. I faced connection state management issues. I broke the problem down, studied the documentation, built a proof of concept, then integrated it cleanly into the main project and delivered on time. It taught me to stay systematic under pressure.' },
      { question: 'Where do you see yourself in 3 years?', answer: 'I see myself as a strong mid-level frontend developer who has shipped multiple production features, with expertise in performance optimisation and design systems. I want to deepen my knowledge of Next.js and web accessibility. My goal is to be someone the team relies on for good architectural decisions.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle feedback and criticism?', answer: 'I welcome feedback because it is how I improve. I treat code review comments as learning opportunities. If I disagree I discuss it respectfully and stay open to being wrong. I have proactively asked senior developers to review my work even when not required.' },
      { question: 'How do you prioritise tasks with multiple deadlines?', answer: 'I list all tasks, estimate effort, and identify dependencies — what is blocking other work — and prioritise those first. I communicate proactively if a deadline is at risk. I use time-blocking and adapt when priorities shift, because requirements change in real projects.' },
      { question: 'Why do you want to work at this company?', answer: 'I researched your product and am impressed by the UX quality and frontend engineering challenges your team solves. I want to work somewhere where frontend is treated as a serious engineering discipline. Your engineering blog and open-source contributions show quality and learning are priorities, which aligns with how I want to develop.' },
      { question: 'How do you keep up with frontend technology?', answer: 'I follow React and JavaScript Weekly newsletters, official framework blogs, and podcasts like Syntax.fm. I build small experimental projects on weekends with new tools before adopting them. This keeps me current without chasing every trend blindly.' },
      { question: 'How do you ensure your code is maintainable?', answer: 'I write components with single responsibility, name variables descriptively, add comments only where the "why" is not obvious, write tests for critical logic, and keep files small. I do self-review before PRs — reading my code as if I were the reviewer catches many issues early.' },
      { question: 'Do you have any questions for us?', answer: 'How does your team approach code reviews — is it primarily quality-focused or does it have mentorship built in? What does onboarding look like for new frontend developers? And what are the biggest frontend challenges the team is currently tackling? I ask to understand where I can contribute and what I will learn.' },
    ],
  },

  'Backend Developer': {
    technical: [
      { question: 'What is the difference between REST and GraphQL?', answer: 'REST uses fixed endpoints where each URL represents a resource and HTTP methods define the action. GraphQL uses a single endpoint where clients specify exactly what data they need, eliminating over-fetching and under-fetching. REST is better for simple cacheable APIs; GraphQL shines when clients have diverse data needs.' },
      { question: 'How does JWT authentication work end-to-end?', answer: 'The user logs in, the server verifies credentials, creates a JWT signed with a secret key containing the user ID, and returns it. The client sends it in the Authorization: Bearer header on subsequent requests. The server verifies the signature without hitting the database on every request, making it stateless and scalable.' },
      { question: 'Explain database indexing and when to use it.', answer: 'An index allows the database to find rows without a full table scan. I add indexes on columns in WHERE clauses, JOIN conditions, and ORDER BY. However indexes slow writes and use storage, so I avoid over-indexing. I check query execution plans to confirm indexes are being used.' },
      { question: 'What are ACID properties in databases?', answer: 'Atomicity: transactions fully complete or fully rollback. Consistency: database moves between valid states. Isolation: concurrent transactions do not interfere. Durability: committed transactions persist through failures. Essential for financial and booking systems where data integrity is critical.' },
      { question: 'What is middleware in Express.js?', answer: 'Middleware are functions with access to req, res, and next in the request-response cycle. They execute sequentially and can modify requests, end responses, or pass to the next middleware. I use them for authentication, logging, validation, error handling, and rate limiting — keeping these separate from business logic.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle errors in an Express API?', answer: 'I use centralised error handling middleware placed at the end of the stack. Route handlers pass errors using next(error). This middleware normalises all errors into consistent JSON responses. I wrap async handlers with a utility that catches rejected promises automatically, avoiding try-catch in every controller.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between SQL and NoSQL databases?', answer: 'SQL databases store data in structured tables with schemas and support powerful JOINs — ideal for complex relational data and transactions. NoSQL databases like MongoDB store flexible documents — ideal for unstructured data, rapid schema changes, and horizontal scaling. I choose based on relationship complexity and consistency requirements.' },
      { question: 'What is rate limiting and how do you implement it?', answer: 'Rate limiting restricts requests per client in a time window to prevent abuse and brute force attacks. I use express-rate-limit middleware. For distributed systems I use Redis as the shared store so limits apply across all server instances. Sensitive routes like /login get stricter limits than general routes.' },
      { question: 'Explain the difference between authentication and authorisation.', answer: 'Authentication verifies who you are — confirming identity through credentials or tokens. Authorisation determines what you are allowed to do — checking permissions after identity is confirmed. In my APIs, JWT verification happens first (authentication), then role-based checks (authorisation). Confusing these causes common security vulnerabilities.' },
      { question: 'What is connection pooling?', answer: 'Connection pooling maintains a cache of open database connections for reuse rather than opening a new one per request. Opening connections is expensive — it involves network handshakes and authentication. With pooling, connections are checked out, used, and returned. Mongoose handles this automatically with a configurable pool size, improving throughput under load.' },
    ],
    conceptual: [
      { question: 'What is horizontal vs vertical scaling?', answer: 'Vertical scaling adds more resources to an existing server — simpler but has physical limits. Horizontal scaling adds more servers and distributes load — complex but essentially limitless. Modern cloud architectures prefer horizontal scaling with load balancers and stateless application design. My APIs are stateless precisely to support horizontal scaling.' },
      { question: 'Explain the CAP theorem.', answer: 'A distributed system can guarantee at most two of three: Consistency (all nodes see the same data), Availability (every request gets a response), and Partition Tolerance (system works despite network partitions). Since partitions are unavoidable, you choose between CP or AP. MongoDB is AP by default; PostgreSQL leans CP.' },
      { question: 'What is a message queue and when would you use one?', answer: 'A message queue enables asynchronous communication — one service puts a message in the queue and another processes it independently. I use one for tasks that do not need to complete synchronously: sending emails, processing images, generating reports. This decouples services, improves resilience, and prevents slow tasks from blocking API responses.' },
      { question: 'What is microservices architecture?', answer: 'Microservices split an application into independently deployable services that own specific business capabilities and communicate over APIs or message queues. Benefits include independent scaling, isolated failures, and technology flexibility. Downsides include operational complexity and distributed tracing challenges. I recommend starting with a monolith and extracting services only when there is a clear reason.' },
      { question: 'What is caching and what are common strategies?', answer: 'Caching stores frequently accessed data in fast storage to avoid expensive recomputation. Strategies: cache-aside (check cache first, load from DB on miss), write-through (writes go to both cache and DB), write-behind (writes go to cache first, DB updated asynchronously). Cache invalidation — knowing when to expire data — is the hardest part.' },
      { question: 'How does a load balancer work?', answer: 'A load balancer distributes traffic across server instances using algorithms like round-robin, least connections, or IP hashing. It performs health checks and stops routing to unhealthy instances. This prevents any single server from being overwhelmed and improves reliability.' },
      { question: 'What is API versioning and why is it important?', answer: 'API versioning allows evolving your API without breaking existing clients. Breaking changes get a new version (/api/v2/) while /api/v1/ remains available. Without versioning, any change risks breaking integrations. I include version in URL paths and maintain older versions until clients migrate, communicating deprecation timelines.' },
      { question: 'What is Docker and why is it useful?', answer: 'Docker packages an application with all dependencies into a container that runs consistently anywhere. This eliminates environment inconsistency issues. For backend work it means spinning up isolated databases, running services locally without installation, and defining the entire stack in docker-compose.yml. It also simplifies cloud deployment.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between synchronous and asynchronous processing?', answer: 'Synchronous processing blocks until the operation completes. Asynchronous processing initiates an operation and continues — the result is handled later via callbacks, promises, or events. In Node.js all I/O is asynchronous because it runs on a single thread; blocking it with synchronous I/O would halt all request handling.' },
      { question: 'What are environment variables and why are they important for security?', answer: 'Environment variables store configuration outside the codebase — database URIs, API keys, JWT secrets. Hardcoding secrets in source code risks exposing them in version control. Different environments need different values, and env vars make switching seamless. I always add .env to .gitignore and provide a .env.example with placeholders.' },
    ],
    hr: [
      { question: 'Tell me about yourself.', answer: 'I am a backend developer with strong skills in Node.js, Express, and MongoDB. I have built production-grade REST APIs, implemented JWT authentication, and worked with both SQL and NoSQL databases. I enjoy solving complex data and performance problems and take pride in writing clean, well-structured code.' },
      { question: 'Describe a time you improved system performance.', answer: 'Our API response times degraded significantly as data grew. I profiled and found N+1 queries on a popular endpoint — fetching a list then querying each item separately. I refactored to a single MongoDB aggregation with a lookup stage. Response time dropped from 1200ms to under 150ms. It taught me to check query patterns early.' },
      { question: 'How do you approach debugging a production issue?', answer: 'I gather information first: check logs, identify when the issue started, look for recent deployments. I form a hypothesis and test it with minimal disruption — checking metrics or replaying a request in staging. I fix the immediate issue to restore service, then do a proper root cause analysis and add monitoring to catch it earlier next time.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle working under pressure?', answer: 'I stay focused on what is controllable: break the problem into the smallest actionable step, do it, then reassess. I communicate status proactively rather than going silent. Most pressure comes from uncertainty, so keeping everyone informed reduces it. I have learned that most issues have solutions — it is a matter of finding them systematically.' },
      { question: 'What is your approach to writing clean code?', answer: 'Clean code means code a colleague can understand without asking questions. I aim for descriptive naming, small focused functions, consistent formatting via ESLint and Prettier, and separation of concerns — business logic in services, not route handlers. I treat tests as documentation: good test names explain what the code should do.' },
      { question: 'Where do you see yourself in 3 years?', answer: 'I want to design systems, not just implement features. In three years I aim to have experience with distributed systems, event-driven architecture, and cloud infrastructure where I can make architectural recommendations confidently. I also want to mentor junior developers — teaching is one of the best ways to deepen your own understanding.' },
      { question: 'How do you learn new technologies?', answer: 'Read-build-review. I start with official documentation, immediately build something small — even a toy project — because building forces understanding. I then review against best practices and refactor. For backend technologies I specifically look for real-world production patterns, not just hello-world examples.' },
      { question: 'Tell me about a time you disagreed with a technical decision.', answer: 'The team decided to use a shared global object for session data instead of Redis. I raised scalability concerns during design. The team proceeded due to timeline. I documented my concerns, implemented it as decided, and ensured we had a migration plan. It broke under load testing and we migrated as planned. I learned to voice concerns clearly but respect team decisions.' },
      { question: 'Why do you want to work in backend development?', answer: 'I enjoy the precision of backend work — designing data models, optimising queries, securing APIs, building reliable systems. Backend decisions have long-lasting impact: a well-designed API can serve a product for years. I find myself most engaged when thinking through edge cases, concurrency, and how systems behave at scale.' },
      { question: 'Do you have any questions for us?', answer: 'What does your deployment process look like and how often does the backend team ship to production? How does the team handle on-call and incident response? And what is the biggest technical challenge your backend is currently facing? That helps me understand where I could contribute most.' },
    ],
  },

  'Full Stack Developer': {
    technical: [
      { question: 'Explain the MERN stack and how components interact.', answer: 'MERN: MongoDB (NoSQL database), Express (Node.js web framework), React (frontend library), Node.js (JavaScript runtime). React sends HTTP requests via Axios, Express routes handle them, business logic runs in Node.js services, data is read/written to MongoDB, and JSON responses return to React for rendering.' },
      { question: 'How do you manage state in a large React application?', answer: 'Local state: useState. Shared nearby state: lift up. Global state: Context for simple cases, Zustand or Redux Toolkit for complex cases. Server state: React Query or SWR which handle caching, background refetching, and loading states more elegantly than storing server data in client state management.' },
      { question: 'How does end-to-end JWT authentication work in MERN?', answer: 'User logs in, Express verifies credentials against MongoDB with bcrypt, creates a JWT with user ID, and returns it. React stores the token and attaches it to every API request in the Authorization header. Express middleware verifies the JWT signature and decodes the payload on protected routes without querying MongoDB.' },
      { question: 'What is CORS and how do you handle it?', answer: 'CORS is a browser security mechanism blocking cross-origin requests. Browsers send a preflight OPTIONS request to check server permissions. In Express I use the cors middleware, configuring allowed origins, methods, and headers. In development I allow localhost:3000; in production I restrict to the actual frontend domain.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between cookies and localStorage for tokens?', answer: 'localStorage is accessible from JavaScript — convenient but vulnerable to XSS attacks. HttpOnly cookies cannot be accessed from JavaScript, immune to XSS but vulnerable to CSRF (mitigated with CSRF tokens). For high-security production apps, HttpOnly cookies are preferred. For learning projects, localStorage is common for simplicity.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle file uploads in a MERN app?', answer: 'Frontend uses a file input with FormData. Backend uses Multer middleware to parse multipart data — storing files in memory as buffers for processing. For production I stream to cloud storage like AWS S3 or Cloudinary rather than the server filesystem. The URL is then saved to MongoDB.' },
      { question: 'How do you deploy a MERN application?', answer: 'Frontend builds to static files (npm run build) deployed to Vercel or Netlify. Backend deploys to Railway or Render with environment variables configured in the dashboard. MongoDB runs on Atlas. In Vite\'s vite.config.js I proxy /api to localhost:5000 in development; production uses the deployed backend URL.' },
      { question: 'What is Mongoose and what does it provide?', answer: 'Mongoose is an ODM for MongoDB providing schema definition with type checking, validation, middleware hooks, instance methods, and virtual properties. Rather than raw MongoDB queries, I define schemas that document data shape and enforce it. This catches data quality issues early and makes code more self-documenting.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle errors across the full stack?', answer: 'Backend: centralised error middleware returning consistent JSON with meaningful messages. Frontend: try-catch around API calls, user-friendly error toasts, never exposing raw errors to users. Global React error boundaries catch rendering errors. Logging to Sentry catches production issues proactively.' },
      { question: 'How do you optimise API performance?', answer: 'Database: indexes on queried fields, projection to return only needed fields, avoiding N+1 queries. API: Redis caching for frequently read data, pagination, compression middleware. Infrastructure: CDN for static assets, load balancing. I always measure first with profiling tools before optimising.' },
    ],
    conceptual: [
      { question: 'How do you balance frontend and backend work?', answer: 'I design the API contract first — request/response shape — before writing code on either side. This lets both sides work in parallel using mock data on the frontend. I context-switch deliberately, completing backend features before moving to frontend implementation, with Postman documentation keeping both sides aligned.' },
      { question: 'What is separation of concerns in full-stack development?', answer: 'Each part of the system has a single responsibility. React components handle rendering; API routes handle routing and validation; service files contain business logic; models handle persistence. This makes each layer testable in isolation, easier to modify, and more readable to collaborators.' },
      { question: 'What is technical debt and how do you manage it?', answer: 'Technical debt is the cost of shortcuts — quick fixes, skipped tests, duplicated code. I manage it by addressing small debts immediately, scheduling refactoring time for larger debts, and tracking known issues in a backlog with estimated effort. Making debt visible to the team is key so it gets prioritised alongside features.' },
      { question: 'What is the role of testing in a full-stack project?', answer: 'Testing is my safety net for refactoring. Backend: unit tests for service logic, integration tests for API endpoints with Supertest. Frontend: component tests with React Testing Library focusing on user behaviour. E2E tests with Cypress for critical user flows. I prioritise tests for complex business logic and security-sensitive code.' },
      { question: 'How do you approach designing a new feature?', answer: 'Start with the user story, design the data model, define API endpoints, sketch the UI. Ask: what validations are needed? What are the edge cases? Build a walking skeleton end-to-end quickly — even if basic — then iterate. This gives the team something visible early and reduces the risk of building the wrong thing.' },
      { question: 'What security practices do you follow?', answer: 'Never store plain-text passwords (always bcrypt). HTTPS everywhere. Validate and sanitise all inputs server-side. Rate limit sensitive endpoints. Never expose sensitive data in API responses. Keep dependencies updated. Use environment variables for all secrets. Security is not added later — it is built in from the start.' },
      { question: 'What is the importance of API documentation?', answer: 'API documentation is the contract between frontend and backend teams. It reduces integration errors, speeds development, and is essential for onboarding. I use Postman collections for internal teams and Swagger/OpenAPI for public APIs. Writing documentation before implementing forces clear API design thinking.' },
      { question: 'How do you ensure a good user experience?', answer: 'UX decisions happen at every layer. Fast API responses prevent frustration. Proper loading states, error states with actionable messages, optimistic updates for snappy feel, and empty states that guide users are all important. I design for mobile from the start and test with actual users rather than only developer assumptions.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle ambiguous requirements?', answer: 'I ask clarifying questions early rather than making assumptions. I identify the core user need behind the requirement, propose a concrete approach with a mockup to confirm alignment before building. If genuinely ambiguous, I surface options and trade-offs rather than picking one silently.' },
      { question: 'What is microservices vs monolithic architecture?', answer: 'A monolith is a single deployable unit — simpler to develop, test, and deploy, appropriate for most startups. Microservices split into independently deployable services — better for large teams with different scaling needs. I start with a well-structured monolith and extract services only when there is a clear, specific reason.' },
    ],
    hr: [
      { question: 'Tell me about yourself.', answer: 'I am a full-stack developer comfortable across the entire web stack — React and Tailwind on the frontend, Node.js, Express, and MongoDB on the backend. I have built and deployed complete web applications including an e-commerce platform and a real-time analytics dashboard. I enjoy owning features end-to-end and I am looking for a role where I can contribute immediately and grow into a senior full-stack position.' },
      { question: 'Describe a project you built from scratch.', answer: 'I built a full-stack task management app. I designed the MongoDB schema, built the Express API with JWT authentication and role-based access, then built the React UI with a Kanban board and drag-and-drop. I deployed to Vercel and Railway. The experience taught me how much more work production-readiness requires compared to getting basics working.' },
      { question: 'How do you stay motivated when stuck?', answer: 'I give myself 30-45 minutes of focused debugging, then step back. I articulate the problem in writing — rubber duck debugging — which often reveals the issue. I then seek help without hesitation, because asking is a skill not a weakness. A short break resets perspective; I have solved many problems on a walk.' },
      { question: 'What is your greatest weakness?', answer: 'I sometimes perfect a solution when a simpler approach would suffice. I actively work on this by time-boxing exploration phases and asking "what is the simplest thing that could work?" before going deep. This has improved delivery speed without meaningfully impacting quality.' },
      { question: 'Describe a time you worked in a team under a deadline.', answer: 'During a 48-hour hackathon, our team of four built a complete web application. I handled the backend API while teammates built the frontend. We used a shared Postman collection as the API contract and synced every two hours. When the frontend team had issues with an API response shape, I adjusted it on the backend. We won second place.' },
      { question: 'Why full-stack rather than specialising?', answer: 'Full-stack gives me complete problem ownership. When I encounter a bug I can trace it from database through API to UI without handoff. Understanding both sides makes me better at each — knowing frontend needs helps me design better APIs, and backend knowledge helps me make smarter data-fetching decisions.' },
      { question: 'How do you prioritise when you have more tasks than time?', answer: 'I use an impact-effort matrix. High-impact, low-effort goes first. High-impact, high-effort gets broken into visible progress chunks. Low-impact gets deferred. I communicate proactively — if something is at risk, I flag it early so the team can reprioritise rather than discover it at the deadline.' },
      { question: 'Where do you see yourself in 3 years?', answer: 'As a strong mid-level full-stack developer who has shipped significant features to production, with growing expertise in distributed systems and cloud architecture. I also want to mentor junior developers, as teaching is one of the best ways to deepen understanding. Long-term I am drawn to full-stack technical leadership.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle feedback?', answer: 'I welcome feedback because it accelerates growth. I treat code review comments as learning opportunities. If I disagree I discuss respectfully and stay open to being wrong. I also proactively seek review from senior developers on important work because outside perspective catches issues I normalise.' },
      { question: 'Do you have any questions for us?', answer: 'How is work structured — do developers own features end-to-end or is there a strict frontend/backend split? I enjoy the full ownership model. What does code review culture look like? And what is the biggest technical challenge you are hoping to address in the next six months? That helps me understand where I could contribute most.' },
    ],
  },

  'Data Analyst': {
    technical: [
      { question: 'Write a SQL query to find the top 5 customers by total revenue.', answer: 'SELECT c.name, SUM(o.order_amount) AS total_revenue FROM orders o JOIN customers c ON o.customer_id = c.id GROUP BY c.id, c.name ORDER BY total_revenue DESC LIMIT 5. In practice I would also check for NULLs and decide whether to include cancelled orders based on the business requirement.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle missing values in a dataset?', answer: 'My approach depends on extent and pattern. For numerical columns with few missing values, I impute with the median. For categorical, I use the mode or add an "Unknown" category. Over 40% missing, I evaluate dropping the column. I also check whether data is missing at random or not — MNAR often indicates a systematic data collection issue to fix upstream.' },
      { question: 'Explain INNER JOIN, LEFT JOIN, and FULL OUTER JOIN.', answer: 'INNER JOIN returns only rows matching in both tables. LEFT JOIN returns all left table rows and matching right rows — non-matching right rows are NULL, useful when you want all primary table records regardless of related records. FULL OUTER JOIN returns all rows from both tables with NULLs where there is no match — useful for reconciliation.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between HAVING and WHERE in SQL?', answer: 'WHERE filters rows before aggregation — operates on individual rows. HAVING filters after aggregation — operates on grouped results. Example: WHERE status = "active" filters before GROUP BY; HAVING AVG(salary) > 50000 filters groups after aggregation. You cannot use aggregate functions in WHERE.' },
      { question: 'How do you perform exploratory data analysis?', answer: 'I follow a structured process: check shape and dtypes, examine missing values and duplicates, look at distributions via descriptive statistics and histograms, analyse categorical columns with value counts, check correlations with a heatmap, then explore variable relationships with scatter or box plots. EDA reveals what cleaning is needed and patterns that inform the analysis.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between a bar chart and a histogram?', answer: 'A bar chart shows categorical data with separated bars representing categories. A histogram shows the distribution of continuous numerical data grouped into bins with touching bars showing continuity. Bar charts compare categories (sales by region); histograms reveal distribution shape (is this normally distributed? Does it have a long tail?).' },
      { question: 'What is a pivot table?', answer: 'A pivot table summarises data by grouping rows and columns with aggregation functions. In Python: pd.pivot_table(df, values="revenue", index="region", columns="product", aggfunc="sum"). This creates a cross-tabulated view making patterns visible that are hidden in row-level data.' },
      { question: 'Explain window functions in SQL.', answer: 'Window functions calculate across rows related to the current row without collapsing them like GROUP BY. Common ones: ROW_NUMBER(), RANK(), SUM() OVER (running total), LAG()/LEAD() (previous/next row values). Extremely powerful for time-series analysis, running totals, and ranking within groups.' },
      { question: 'How do you detect and handle outliers?', answer: 'I detect outliers visually with box plots and numerically with the IQR method (values below Q1 - 1.5*IQR or above Q3 + 1.5*IQR) or z-scores. How I handle them depends: data errors get corrected or removed; genuine extreme values may be capped (winsorising) or kept. I always document outlier decisions because removing data requires justification.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between correlation and regression?', answer: 'Correlation measures the strength and direction of a linear relationship — symmetrical, coefficient between -1 and 1. Regression models the relationship to predict one variable from another — directional, producing an equation. Correlation answers "how related are X and Y?"; regression answers "what value of Y can I predict from X?".' },
    ],
    conceptual: [
      { question: 'What is A/B testing and how do you determine statistical significance?', answer: 'A/B testing compares two versions to determine which performs better. I split users randomly into control and treatment groups, run for a predetermined duration, and measure the metric. Statistical significance is determined with a hypothesis test — usually a t-test or chi-squared — with p < 0.05. Sample size must be calculated upfront with power analysis.' },
      { question: 'What metrics would you define to measure product health?', answer: 'I categorise metrics by: acquisition (new users, conversion rate), engagement (DAU/MAU, session duration, feature adoption), retention (Day 7/30 retention, churn rate), revenue (MRR, ARPU, LTV), and satisfaction (NPS, support volume). The most important metric depends on the product stage — early stage focuses on engagement; growth stage on acquisition and revenue.' },
      { question: 'Explain descriptive, diagnostic, predictive, and prescriptive analytics.', answer: 'Descriptive answers "what happened?" with historical summaries. Diagnostic answers "why did it happen?" with drill-down and correlation analysis. Predictive answers "what will happen?" with statistical models. Prescriptive answers "what should we do?" with optimisation algorithms. Most organisations are strong at descriptive and mature progressively toward prescriptive.' },
      { question: 'What is data normalisation and when do you need it?', answer: 'Normalisation scales features to a common range so larger-scale features do not dominate. Min-max scales to 0-1; standardisation scales to mean 0, std 1. I apply normalisation before algorithms sensitive to feature scale: k-means, KNN, gradient descent models. Tree-based models like Random Forest do not require normalisation.' },
      { question: 'What is a data pipeline?', answer: 'A data pipeline automates moving data from source systems through extraction, transformation, and loading (ETL) to a destination. It ensures fresh, consistent, clean data without manual intervention. Tools: Airflow orchestrates pipelines, dbt transforms data in the warehouse, Fivetran handles source extraction.' },
      { question: 'How do you communicate findings to non-technical stakeholders?', answer: 'I lead with the business insight and recommendation, not methodology. I use one chart per key finding with plain-language titles stating the finding (not "Figure 1"). I anticipate the "so what?" question and always come with a recommendation or trade-off options. Non-technical audiences care about what it means for them, not the statistics.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between a data analyst and a data scientist?', answer: 'A data analyst focuses on understanding past and present performance — querying databases, building dashboards, communicating insights. A data scientist builds predictive models and runs experiments to anticipate future outcomes. The boundary is blurry and company-specific. I identify as an analyst with growing data science skills.' },
      { question: 'What is data governance?', answer: 'Data governance is policies and standards for managing data — covering data quality, access controls, privacy compliance (GDPR, CCPA), lineage tracking, and documentation. Without governance, the same metric produces different numbers across teams, sensitive data can be accessed by the wrong people, and regulatory violations create legal liability.' },
      { question: 'What is cohort analysis and when would you use it?', answer: 'Cohort analysis groups users by a shared characteristic — usually signup date — and tracks behaviour over time. It is the right tool for understanding retention patterns, identifying whether product changes improved behaviour for new users, or comparing acquisition channels over time. Without it, averages can be misleading as a growing user base dilutes metric changes.' },
      { question: 'How do you validate data quality before analysis?', answer: 'I check completeness (missing values), uniqueness (duplicates), consistency (same values represented differently), validity (values within expected ranges), and accuracy (spot-check against source systems). I also verify row counts against expectations and look for sudden drops or spikes suggesting pipeline issues.' },
    ],
    hr: [
      { question: 'Tell me about yourself.', answer: 'I am a data analyst with strong SQL, Python, and data visualisation skills. I enjoy finding patterns that lead to actionable business decisions. I have worked with customer transaction data and web analytics, and I am comfortable with the full workflow from data cleaning in Python to stakeholder dashboards in Tableau.' },
      { question: 'Describe a data insight that drove a business decision.', answer: 'I noticed users who completed the onboarding tutorial had 60% higher 30-day retention. I presented a cohort analysis showing the retention curves side by side. The team made the tutorial more prominent in the sign-up flow and retention improved 15% in the following cohort. The value of an analyst is not just finding insights but communicating them to drive action.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle situations when data contradicts your hypothesis?', answer: 'I treat it as the analysis working correctly — its purpose is to test assumptions, not confirm them. I double-check methodology to rule out errors, then accept the data\'s answer and present it honestly. Surprising results are often the most valuable findings because they challenge assumptions guiding decisions without scrutiny.' },
      { question: 'How do you prioritise multiple analysis requests?', answer: 'I assess by business impact (how much does the enabled decision matter?) and urgency (when is the decision being made?). I communicate prioritisation transparently — not just "I\'ll get to yours later" but a specific timeline and reason. This prevents frustration from invisible queues and helps stakeholders plan.' },
      { question: 'What tools are you most comfortable with?', answer: 'For querying: SQL (PostgreSQL and MySQL) and Python with Pandas and NumPy. For visualisation: Matplotlib and Seaborn for exploratory work, Tableau or Power BI for stakeholder dashboards. I use Jupyter for notebooks and Excel/Google Sheets for quick collaborative analyses. I am currently learning dbt for data transformation.' },
      { question: 'How do you ensure your analyses are reproducible?', answer: 'I write all cleaning and analysis steps in code, never manual Excel transformations. I version control with Git, document assumptions with comments and markdown cells, and store the exact data snapshot used for a specific analysis. I write clear README files so a colleague can reproduce results without asking me.' },
      { question: 'Describe how you handle a stakeholder who wants data to support a predetermined conclusion.', answer: 'I start by understanding their goal — often they have a reasonable hypothesis based on experience. If data supports their conclusion, great. If not, I present actual findings clearly. I do not manufacture conclusions to please stakeholders because that damages trust. A wrong decision made with false confidence is worse than a difficult honest conversation.' },
      { question: 'How do you keep up with data analytics?', answer: 'I follow Towards Data Science, Data Engineering Weekly newsletter, and the dbt Slack community. I take one structured course per quarter. I work on Kaggle projects to apply new techniques and benchmark against practitioners. Staying current matters because tools and best practices evolve quickly.' },
      { question: 'What is your approach when given a vague analysis request?', answer: 'I ask three questions: What decision will this inform? When does the decision need to be made? What does "good" look like — what makes this actionable? This focuses "analyse our sales data" into a specific scoped question. With that clarity I produce the right analysis rather than a comprehensive but unfocused report.' },
      { question: 'Do you have any questions for us?', answer: 'What does the data stack look like here — how is data collected, stored, and made available? How embedded are analysts in product and business teams? And what is the biggest open analytical question the team is currently working on? This helps me see where I could contribute and what skills I would develop.' },
    ],
  },

  'AI/ML Engineer': {
    technical: [
      { question: 'Explain the bias-variance trade-off.', answer: 'Bias is error from oversimplification — high-bias models underfit. Variance is sensitivity to training data — high-variance models overfit. Reducing bias typically increases variance and vice versa. The goal is finding the sweet spot: complex enough to learn the signal but not so complex it learns the noise. Regularisation, cross-validation, and ensembles help manage this trade-off.' },
      { question: 'What is gradient descent and how does it work?', answer: 'Gradient descent minimises a loss function by iteratively adjusting model parameters opposite to the gradient direction. The learning rate controls step size. Batch gradient descent uses the full dataset — accurate but slow. SGD uses one sample — fast but noisy. Mini-batch (used in practice) balances both. Adam combines momentum and adaptive learning rates for faster convergence.' },
      { question: 'How does backpropagation work?', answer: 'Backpropagation computes gradients of the loss with respect to each weight using the chain rule. Forward pass: input flows through layers producing a prediction and loss. Backward pass: the loss gradient propagates backwards through each layer, computing each weight\'s contribution to the error. These gradients update weights via gradient descent, repeated over many batches until convergence.' },
      { question: 'What is regularisation and what is the difference between L1 and L2?', answer: 'Regularisation adds a penalty to the loss function to discourage large weights, reducing overfitting. L2 (Ridge) penalises squared weights — shrinks all weights towards zero but rarely to exactly zero. L1 (Lasso) penalises absolute weights — can drive some to exactly zero, performing feature selection. I use L2 by default and L1 when many features are likely irrelevant.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between precision and recall?', answer: 'Precision: of all positive predictions, how many are correct (TP / (TP + FP)). Recall: of all actual positives, how many were found (TP / (TP + FN)). For spam detection, high precision matters — avoid flagging legitimate email. For cancer screening, high recall matters — avoid missing actual cases. F1-score is the harmonic mean balancing both.' },
      { question: 'What is cross-validation and why is it important?', answer: 'Cross-validation evaluates model performance on unseen data more reliably than a single train-test split. In k-fold CV, data splits into k parts; the model trains on k-1 folds and evaluates on the remaining fold, repeating k times. Results are averaged. Every sample is used for both training and evaluation, giving a lower-variance performance estimate.' },
      { question: 'Explain what a confusion matrix is.', answer: 'A confusion matrix shows: True Positives (correct positive predictions), True Negatives (correct negative predictions), False Positives (predicted positive, actually negative — Type I), False Negatives (predicted negative, actually positive — Type II). I derive precision, recall, accuracy, and F1 from it. For imbalanced classes, accuracy alone is misleading — a model always predicting the majority class has high accuracy but zero utility.' },
      { question: 'What is transfer learning?', answer: 'Transfer learning uses a model pre-trained on a large dataset as the starting point for a related task. The pre-trained model has learned useful representations. I fine-tune it on my specific dataset, typically freezing early layers and training later layers plus a new task-specific head. This dramatically reduces training time, data requirements, and compute — especially when my dataset is small.' },
      { question: 'What is a transformer model?', answer: 'Transformers replaced RNNs for sequence tasks using self-attention mechanisms. Self-attention allows each token to attend to every other token simultaneously, capturing long-range dependencies. Transformers are highly parallelisable, making them GPU-efficient. They are the foundation of BERT, GPT, and virtually all modern NLP models, and have expanded to images (ViT) and other modalities.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle imbalanced datasets?', answer: 'At data level: oversample the minority class using SMOTE or undersample the majority. At algorithm level: use class_weight="balanced" in scikit-learn. At evaluation level: use precision, recall, F1, and AUC-ROC rather than accuracy. For extreme imbalance (fraud at 0.1%), I also consider anomaly detection framing rather than binary classification.' },
    ],
    conceptual: [
      { question: 'What is the difference between supervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement learning?', answer: 'Supervised trains on labelled input-output pairs — classification and regression. Unsupervised finds structure in unlabelled data — clustering, dimensionality reduction. Reinforcement learning trains an agent to take actions maximising cumulative reward through trial and error — used in games, robotics, and recommendations. Most production ML is supervised; reinforcement is powerful but complex.' },
      { question: 'What is overfitting and how do you prevent it?', answer: 'Overfitting means a model learns training noise and fails to generalise. Signs: low training loss, high validation loss. Prevention: regularisation (L1/L2 or dropout in neural networks), cross-validation, early stopping, more training data, data augmentation, reducing model complexity, or ensemble methods. The best first step is always getting more diverse training data.' },
      { question: 'Explain the concept of feature engineering.', answer: 'Feature engineering uses domain knowledge to create or transform input variables that make algorithms work better. It includes creating interaction features, extracting date components, encoding categoricals, normalising numericals, and creating aggregates. Good features can make a simple model outperform a complex model with poor features — it is often where the biggest practical performance gains come from.' },
      { question: 'What are ethical considerations in deploying ML models?', answer: 'Fairness: does the model perform equally across demographic groups? Bias in training data propagates to decisions. Transparency: can decisions be explained to those affected? Privacy: was training data collected with consent? Accountability: who is responsible for harmful decisions? Ongoing monitoring for drift and bias is essential post-deployment. These are not afterthoughts — they must be designed in from the start.' },
      { question: 'What is the curse of dimensionality?', answer: 'As features increase, the feature space volume grows exponentially, making data increasingly sparse. Distance metrics become less meaningful — all points appear roughly equidistant. This hurts algorithms relying on distance (KNN, clustering) and requires exponentially more data. Solutions: dimensionality reduction (PCA, UMAP), feature selection, and regularisation.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between bagging and boosting?', answer: 'Both combine weak learners. Bagging trains models independently on random data subsets and averages predictions — reduces variance. Random Forest is the most famous bagging algorithm. Boosting trains sequentially, each model focusing on previous mistakes — reduces bias. XGBoost and LightGBM are powerful boosting algorithms. Bagging is more parallelisable; boosting typically achieves better performance but is more prone to overfitting.' },
      { question: 'What is model drift and how do you monitor for it?', answer: 'Model drift is performance degradation in production because real-world data distribution shifts from training data. Data drift: input feature distributions change. Concept drift: input-output relationships change. I monitor by tracking performance metrics over time and alerting when feature distribution statistics shift significantly. Tools like Evidently AI and Arize help automate monitoring.' },
      { question: 'Explain the attention mechanism in transformers.', answer: 'Attention allows a model to weigh relevance of different input parts for each output token. For each position, it computes query (Q), key (K), and value (V) vectors. Attention score: softmax(QK^T / √dk)V. The dot product of queries and keys gives attention weights applied to values. Multi-head attention runs multiple operations in parallel, attending to different aspects simultaneously.' },
      { question: 'What is the difference between parametric and non-parametric models?', answer: 'Parametric models have a fixed parameter count — linear regression, logistic regression, neural networks. Faster to train and predict, need less data, but capacity is limited. Non-parametric models grow with training data — KNN, kernel SVM. More flexible but slower at prediction and require more memory. Choose based on data size and prediction speed requirements.' },
      { question: 'What is MLOps and why is it important?', answer: 'MLOps applies DevOps principles to ML — covering data versioning, experiment tracking, model deployment, monitoring, and retraining. Building a model is only 20% of the work; making it reliable in production is the other 80%. Without MLOps, models become unmaintainable — you cannot reproduce experiments, roll back bad models, or detect degradation. Tools: MLflow, DVC, BentoML.' },
    ],
    hr: [
      { question: 'Tell me about yourself.', answer: 'I am an aspiring ML engineer with strong Python, machine learning algorithms, and deep learning frameworks including TensorFlow and PyTorch. I have built end-to-end projects including sentiment analysis, a recommendation system, and an image classification pipeline. I take the full lifecycle seriously — from data quality to model monitoring — and I am looking for a role where I can apply these skills on meaningful problems.' },
      { question: 'Describe an end-to-end ML project you built.', answer: 'I built a movie recommendation system using collaborative filtering. I started with exploratory analysis of a MovieLens dataset, cleaned the data, handled sparse ratings, and built a matrix factorisation model using SVD. I evaluated it with RMSE and precision@K, then built a Flask API to serve recommendations and deployed it. The project taught me how much work data preprocessing is relative to model building.' },
      { question: 'How do you approach a new ML problem?', answer: 'Start by understanding the business problem and how model output will be used — this determines whether I need high precision, recall, explainability, or low latency. Assess available data. Establish a simple baseline to benchmark against. Iterate on feature engineering and model selection with cross-validation. Move to complex models only if simpler ones are insufficient. Touch the test set only at the end.' },
      { question: 'How do you explain a complex model to non-technical stakeholders?', answer: 'I focus on what the model does, not how it works. For a classifier: "The model looks at 15 signals from customer behaviour and assigns a risk score from 1 to 100. Customers above 70 are flagged." I use analogies and domain examples. If explainability matters for trust or regulation, I use SHAP values to show which factors drove a specific prediction.' },
      { question: 'What is your greatest strength as an ML engineer?', answer: 'Approaching ML problems rigorously from first principles. I resist jumping straight to complex models — I always start with a strong baseline, understand the data deeply before modelling, and choose evaluation metrics aligned with the actual business goal. This has saved me from building impressive-sounding models that solve the wrong problem, the most common failure mode in applied ML.' },
      { question: 'How do you stay current with ML research?', answer: 'I follow Papers With Code ArXiv summaries, read two or three papers per week focusing on practical architectures, and subscribe to The Batch by deeplearning.ai. I replicate key papers in code — actually implementing a paper is the best way to deeply understand it. I participate in Kaggle competitions to apply new techniques and benchmark against other practitioners.' },
      { question: 'Describe a time your model did not perform as expected.', answer: 'I built a churn prediction model with 92% accuracy — excellent until I realised the dataset was 92% non-churners, so predicting no churn trivially achieved that score. I had used the wrong metric. I rebuilt evaluation using F1 and AUC-ROC, retrained with class balancing, and actual performance was more modest but genuinely useful. I now define metrics before training, not after seeing results.' },
      { question: 'How do you handle messy real-world data?', answer: 'I treat data cleaning as a first-class engineering task. I document every transformation and why — making the pipeline reproducible and auditable. I write data validation checks that fail loudly if assumptions are violated. I make explicit decisions on missing data and document the rationale. I try to fix problems at the source when possible, because downstream cleaning is a band-aid that must be reapplied for every new data pull.' },
      { question: 'Where do you see yourself in 3 years?', answer: 'As a mid-level ML engineer who has shipped models to production, maintained them through drift and retraining cycles, and understands the full MLOps lifecycle. I am particularly interested in large language models and their practical applications. I also want to contribute to open-source ML tools — it is the best way to engage with the broader community and get feedback from experienced practitioners.' },
      { question: 'Do you have any questions for us?', answer: 'What does the model lifecycle look like here — specifically monitoring after deployment and the retraining process? What is the balance between research and applying existing techniques to business problems? And what ML infrastructure do you use — cloud ML platforms like SageMaker or Vertex AI, or more custom infrastructure? These details help me understand the technical environment I would be working in.' },
    ],
  },
}

const generateQuestions = (role) => {
  return QUESTIONS[role] || QUESTIONS['Full Stack Developer']
}

module.exports = { generateQuestions, QUESTIONS }
